Deployed pfSense Firewall/Router
VM Specs

OS : pfSense CE 2.8.1
RAM : 1 GB
CPU : 1 vCPU
Disk : 20 GB
Adapter 1 : NAT (WAN)
Adapter 2 : Internal Network labnet (LAN)

IP Configuration

WAN : 10.0.2.15 (assigned automatically by VirtualBox NAT)
LAN : 192.168.10.254

Steps

Created VM in VirtualBox with two network adapters (NAT + Internal Network)
Mounted pfSense CE ISO and completed installation
Assigned WAN to em0 and LAN to em1 via console menu
Changed LAN IP from default 192.168.1.1 to 192.168.10.254 via console menu (option 2)
Configured DHCP server on LAN : range 192.168.10.100 → 192.168.10.199
Confirmed web interface accessible at 192.168.10.254
Confirmed internet access from Windows 10 client through pfSense

Troubleshooting

CPU error (long mode) : pfSense VM was set to 32-bit. Fixed by changing VirtualBox VM version to FreeBSD 64-bit in General settings.
APIC panic error : pfSense crashed with "running without device atpic requires a local APIC". Fixed by enabling I/O APIC in VirtualBox System → Motherboard settings.
Wrong ISO : Initially downloaded pfSense Plus (Netgate commercial version) instead of pfSense CE. Switched to pfSense Community Edition which is designed for third-party hardware.
Duplicate VDI conflict : VirtualBox threw an error about duplicate disk UUID after multiple failed attempts. Fixed by removing old disks via File → Virtual Media Manager and creating a fresh VM.
Wrong subnet : pfSense LAN defaulted to 192.168.1.1 but Windows Server was on 192.168.10.0/24. Changed pfSense LAN IP to 192.168.10.254 via pfSense console menu to match the lab subnet.
Two network adapters on Windows Server : Windows Server had two adapters — one on 192.168.10.0/24 and one on 192.168.1.0/24 left over from initial setup. Disabled the second adapter in VirtualBox settings.
DNS not resolving : ping 8.8.8.8 worked but ping google.com failed. Root cause was DNS pointing to Windows Server which was powered off. Internet restored after starting Windows Server.
